      <div class="space-y-8">
        <div class="bg-white border-[3px] border-amber-200 p-6">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-3">Should jewelry designers sell on own website or marketplaces like Etsy?</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3"><strong>Own website = higher margins, brand control. Etsy = discovery, lower margins.</strong> LunaMarie Jewelry: Etsy sales (15% fee + 3% payment processing = 18% total) vs. own site (2.9% Shopify payment = 2.9% total). On $1,500 ring: Etsy keeps $270, own site keeps $43. $227 difference per sale. But Etsy provides discovery (built-in audience searching jewelry). Own site requires driving traffic yourself (Instagram, Pinterest, SEO, ads).</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Hybrid approach wins: Start Etsy for discovery, build own site simultaneously for higher-margin direct sales.</strong> LunaMarie strategy: Etsy for new customer acquisition (15% of sales, buyers find through search), own site for repeat buyers (85% of sales, Instagram followers, email list). Result: Average order value $1,200 on own site vs. $680 on Etsy (repeat buyers know quality, spend more). Own site profit margin 67% vs. Etsy 52%. Long-term: Phase out Etsy as email list grows (own site 0% customer acquisition cost, email marketing = free). When to quit Etsy? When email list revenue exceeds Etsy revenue (typically 12-18 months). Build own site from day 1, use Etsy as discovery engine, graduate to own site as brand matures.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border-[3px] border-yellow-200 p-6">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-3">How do jewelry designers photograph pieces effectively without expensive equipment?</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3"><strong>Smartphone + natural light + $30 reflector = professional jewelry photos. No $5,000 camera needed.</strong> LunaMarie photographed entire collection with iPhone 14 Pro + north-facing window ($30 silver reflector fill light). Setup: Jewelry on white velvet (eliminates color cast), window light from left, reflector on right bouncing light back into shadows. iPhone macro mode (0.5x) captures extreme close-ups of hallmarks, stone settings.</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Editing: Snapseed free app (adjust brightness, contrast, sharpen). No Photoshop subscription needed.</strong> Process: Shoot 20 photos per piece, select best 3, edit in Snapseed (brightness +10, contrast +15, sharpen +20), export 2000px width (web optimized). Total time: 45 minutes per piece. LunaMarie's product photography budget: $800 (iPhone already owned + $30 reflector + $50 white velvet background + $720 for 15 hours shooting/editing @ $48/hr value of designer time). Result: Macro photos so detailed customers asked "what camera did you use?" Answer: iPhone + window light. Professional gear NOT required for jewelry photography. Lighting + composition > camera quality.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border-[3px] border-amber-300 p-6">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-3">When should jewelry designers offer custom orders vs. ready-to-ship only?</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3"><strong>Custom orders = higher revenue, more time. Ready-to-ship = faster fulfillment, lower touch.</strong> LunaMarie tested both: Ready-to-ship pieces (completed inventory, ships 24 hours) = $8,400/month (12 pieces @ $700 average). Custom orders (bespoke requests, 4-6 week lead time) = $8,400/month (4 pieces @ $2,100 average). Same revenue, 4x fewer pieces to fulfill (custom = higher touch, higher price).</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Custom order sweet spot: Offer after 6 months business, when production workflow established.</strong> Before 6 months? Focus on ready-to-ship (build portfolio, fulfill quickly, learn production). After 6 months? Add custom order form to website (LunaMarie's custom requests increased from 2/month to 12/month after prominent form). Pricing: Custom = 3x ready-to-ship (covers design time + client communication). LunaMarie's pricing: Ready-to-ship ring $700, custom same design starting at $2,100. Why 3x? Design consultation (2 hours), CAD modeling (4 hours), casting/fabrication (same as ready), client communication (3 hours emails/video calls), revisions (1 round included). Total overhead: 10 hours @ $100/hr = $1,000. $2,100 custom price - $1,000 overhead = $1,100 profit (vs. $700 ready-to-ship - $200 materials = $500 profit). Higher profit per piece, more time investment. Custom orders scale limited by designer time (max 4-6 pieces/month solo). Ready-to-ship scales unlimited (inventory production during slow periods).</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border-[3px] border-yellow-300 p-6">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-3">How do jewelry designers reduce returns from improper sizing?</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3"><strong>Ring size guide prominent + printable tool + how-to video = 53% fewer returns.</strong> LunaMarie's returns pre-guide: 23% (nearly 1 in 4 rings returned for sizing). After adding sizing guide prominently on every product page: 11% returns (53% reduction). Guide includes: Printable ring sizer PDF (customers print, cut out, measure existing ring), how-to measure video (shows proper technique, common mistakes), size comparison chart (US vs. EU vs. UK sizes), recommendation ("size up if between sizes, can resize down locally").</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Offer free resizing within 30 days = converts hesitant buyers, reduces returns.</strong> LunaMarie added "Free resizing within 30 days" to product descriptions. Result: 34% more sales (buyers confident size can be adjusted), returns unchanged 11% (some buyers still return, but more bought overall). Resizing cost: $12 local jeweler (LunaMarie doesn't have equipment). Absorbed as cost of customer acquisition (cheaper than lost sale). Alternative: Include half-sizes in inventory (size 5.5, 6.5, 7.5) reduces returns 23% but increases inventory carrying cost 40%. Trade-off: Free resizing cheaper than stocking half-sizes for emerging lines. Stock half-sizes when exceeding $25K monthly sales.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border-[3px] border-amber-400 p-6">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-3">Should jewelry designers pursue wholesale accounts or focus on direct-to-consumer?</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3"><strong>Direct-to-consumer first (build brand, higher margins). Wholesale later (scale revenue, brand exposure).</strong> LunaMarie's revenue split: DTC $35,300/month (75% profit margin), wholesale $12,000/month (35% profit margin). DTC more profitable per sale, wholesale scales faster (4 boutiques = $12K without additional marketing). But wholesale requires wholesale pricing (50% off retail = lower margins).</p>
